1
00:00:29,725 --> 00:00:31,379
[INAUDIBLE CONVERSATION]

2
00:03:09,189 --> 00:03:10,190
Hello.

3
00:03:21,636 --> 00:03:22,637
Are you in here?

4
00:03:25,422 --> 00:03:26,423
I got your note.

5
00:03:27,990 --> 00:03:28,991
What do you want?

6
00:03:36,303 --> 00:03:39,001
If this is some kind of a joke,
I don't think it's funny.

7
00:03:43,484 --> 00:03:44,702
I'm going back now.

8
00:04:41,846 --> 00:04:43,283
[AIR HISSING]

9
00:04:55,382 --> 00:04:56,905
[SQUEAKING]

10
00:05:48,217 --> 00:05:49,871
[MAN SPEAKING ON TV]

11
00:05:55,529 --> 00:05:58,445
NICK: Hi. I'm sorry, Sid.
I didn't mean to leaving
you hanging. It's nuts here.

12
00:05:58,488 --> 00:06:00,751
Christina, could you
turn that down, please?

13
00:06:03,275 --> 00:06:05,321
[CLATTERING]

14
00:06:05,365 --> 00:06:07,367
-Christina?
-Oh, no!

15
00:06:08,280 --> 00:06:09,412
Christina.

16
00:06:09,456 --> 00:06:11,980
CHRISTINA:
I was just practicing.

17
00:06:12,023 --> 00:06:14,374
NICK: It's your mother's
favorite lamp.

18
00:06:14,417 --> 00:06:15,766
CHRISTINA: I'm sorry, Dad.

19
00:06:15,810 --> 00:06:19,944
NICK: You smashed it.
Oh, no.

20
00:06:19,988 --> 00:06:22,164
CHRISTINA: I didn't mean it.
It was an accident.

21
00:06:22,207 --> 00:06:23,513
It really was, Dad.

22
00:06:23,557 --> 00:06:26,386
NICK: I know, honey.
I know it was an accident,

23
00:06:26,429 --> 00:06:30,520
but this is why we don't play
T-ball in the house, okay?

24
00:06:30,564 --> 00:06:32,566
CHRISTINA: Okay,
I'll take it outside.

25
00:06:32,609 --> 00:06:36,134
WOMAN ON TV: 
...two tablespoons of raisins, 
three tablespoons of vinegar,

26
00:06:36,178 --> 00:06:38,963
one medium onion, 
two tablespoons of olive oil...

27
00:06:41,183 --> 00:06:42,271
Hello?

28
00:06:48,233 --> 00:06:49,234
Nick?

29
00:06:52,716 --> 00:06:53,848
CHRISTINA: Hey, Mom.

30
00:06:53,891 --> 00:06:55,458
KATE: What's going on here?

31
00:06:55,502 --> 00:06:57,504
NICK: It's under control.

32
00:06:57,547 --> 00:06:59,984
Christina. Chrissy,
how many times
have I told you

33
00:07:00,028 --> 00:07:01,421
not to play T-ball
in the house?

34
00:07:02,291 --> 00:07:03,292
I forgot.

35
00:07:04,641 --> 00:07:06,817
We've been through this
already, okay?

36
00:07:06,861 --> 00:07:07,862
I handled it.

37
00:07:09,907 --> 00:07:11,300
Okay, it's under control.

38
00:07:14,172 --> 00:07:15,435
-[MICROWAVE BEEPING]
-Oh.

39
00:07:22,616 --> 00:07:23,834
Oh.

40
00:07:25,793 --> 00:07:29,274
Dinner is served.

41
00:07:29,318 --> 00:07:32,147
Anyway, they handed me
Roger Pearlman's old office.

42
00:07:32,190 --> 00:07:33,975
You know, the corner one
with the view.

43
00:07:34,018 --> 00:07:35,977
Charlie's been after it
for five years.

44
00:07:36,934 --> 00:07:38,545
Pass the fried rice, please.

45
00:07:38,588 --> 00:07:40,721
Well, they spent a lot of money
to lure you out here...

46
00:07:40,764 --> 00:07:42,462
It's in their best interest
to keep you happy.

47
00:07:42,505 --> 00:07:45,726
Here, sweetie.
Yeah, but Charlie
isn't talking to me now.

48
00:07:45,769 --> 00:07:47,249
This is so ridiculous.

49
00:07:48,598 --> 00:07:50,295
How was your day?

50
00:07:50,339 --> 00:07:52,776
Oh, the usual.
Doing the marketing,
fighting with the butcher,

51
00:07:52,820 --> 00:07:54,604
slaving over a hot stove.

52
00:07:58,129 --> 00:07:59,174
Sweetheart,

53
00:08:00,131 --> 00:08:01,568
you really gonna eat all that?

54
00:08:02,351 --> 00:08:03,570
I'm hungry.

55
00:08:04,658 --> 00:08:06,660
Oh, yeah, and Sid called.

56
00:08:06,703 --> 00:08:08,923
-You got the job?
-I don't know.

57
00:08:08,966 --> 00:08:11,403
The publicity people
at the studio
loved the concept.

58
00:08:11,447 --> 00:08:14,537
There's one more VP
that has to sign off on it,
but...

59
00:08:15,625 --> 00:08:17,627
Sid says I'm a shoo-in.

60
00:08:17,671 --> 00:08:19,499
Honey, that's great.

61
00:08:19,542 --> 00:08:22,153
-Oh, Sid!
-What?

62
00:08:22,197 --> 00:08:25,461
I left him hanging on the phone,
when that little crisis hit
with the lamp.

63
00:08:25,505 --> 00:08:27,985
He must think
I got sucked into a black hole.

64
00:08:37,647 --> 00:08:39,301
You're awfully quiet tonight.

65
00:08:41,782 --> 00:08:43,871
We went to the park
this afternoon.

66
00:08:46,177 --> 00:08:47,744
Nobody was there.

67
00:08:47,788 --> 00:08:50,181
Dad said all the kids
are in summer camp.

68
00:08:52,488 --> 00:08:54,142
I'm sorry.

69
00:08:54,185 --> 00:08:57,188
You know, we tried
to get you in.
We just applied too late.

70
00:08:59,364 --> 00:09:02,585
Nope, he's gone.
Have to call him in the morning.

71
00:09:02,629 --> 00:09:05,414
You know, Anna's gonna be here
in the next couple of days.

72
00:09:05,457 --> 00:09:07,416
You'll get to do lots of things
with her.

73
00:09:07,851 --> 00:09:08,852
Mm-hmm.

74
00:09:11,768 --> 00:09:15,859
Seems to me
we are pinning a lot of hopes
on this girl.

75
00:09:15,903 --> 00:09:18,340
Cooking, cleaning,
taking care of Chrissy.

76
00:09:18,383 --> 00:09:19,994
Big job.

77
00:09:20,037 --> 00:09:22,170
You know, my sister had them
in Paris.

78
00:09:22,213 --> 00:09:23,693
They worked out really well.

79
00:09:23,737 --> 00:09:24,825
Hey, look,

80
00:09:24,868 --> 00:09:26,914
I want it to work
as much as you do.

81
00:09:26,957 --> 00:09:28,785
Probably more. I just don't

82
00:09:28,829 --> 00:09:32,180
harbor any illusions
that she's gonna march in here
like Mary Poppins,

83
00:09:32,223 --> 00:09:33,964
wave her magic umbrella,

84
00:09:35,357 --> 00:09:37,446
and suddenly put our lives
in order.

85
00:09:40,492 --> 00:09:41,581
You never know.

86
00:09:44,671 --> 00:09:47,064
CHRISTINA: Why do they call her
an "old pear," Mom?

87
00:09:47,108 --> 00:09:50,590
[KATE LAUGHS]
You mean "au pair."

88
00:09:50,633 --> 00:09:52,679
I don't know.
It's French for something.

89
00:09:52,722 --> 00:09:54,681
I thought Anna was Swedish.

90
00:09:54,724 --> 00:09:56,421
She is Swedish.

91
00:09:56,465 --> 00:09:58,380
That's just what they call
someone who
looks after children.

92
00:09:58,728 --> 00:09:59,729
Mom?

93
00:10:00,687 --> 00:10:03,472
What if she doesn't like me?

94
00:10:03,515 --> 00:10:06,170
Well, of course
she's gonna like you.
Who doesn't?

95
00:10:06,214 --> 00:10:09,130
I promise, you and Anna
are gonna be
the best of friends.

96
00:10:09,957 --> 00:10:11,698
You know your cousin Sarah.

97
00:10:11,741 --> 00:10:13,787
Her au pair,
they really love each other.

98
00:10:14,744 --> 00:10:15,919
Come on, into bed.

99
00:10:18,922 --> 00:10:20,402
[CHRISTINA GIGGLES]

100
00:10:22,273 --> 00:10:23,274
Hop in.

101
00:10:27,191 --> 00:10:28,453
Cuddle up.

102
00:10:31,935 --> 00:10:33,981
Can you take me
to Mystery Mountain this week?

103
00:10:34,024 --> 00:10:37,332
Hmm. I wish I could.
I've got to work.

104
00:10:37,375 --> 00:10:39,943
You've got to work.
Daddy's got to work.

105
00:10:39,987 --> 00:10:43,599
Well, let's see
what we could do.

106
00:10:43,643 --> 00:10:46,297
We could plan on going
later on in the month.

107
00:10:46,341 --> 00:10:48,038
Oh, but wait a minute.

108
00:10:48,386 --> 00:10:50,388
What?

109
00:10:50,432 --> 00:10:53,914
Daddy says we only go
to Mystery Mountain when
it's a special celebration...,

110
00:10:53,957 --> 00:10:56,438
If only we had
a special celebration coming up.

111
00:10:57,004 --> 00:10:58,222
My birthday.

112
00:10:59,006 --> 00:11:02,183
Your birthday! Of course!

113
00:11:03,227 --> 00:11:05,839
You knew that all the time.

114
00:11:05,882 --> 00:11:06,883
I did.

115
00:11:07,971 --> 00:11:09,364
-Good night.
-Good night.

116
00:11:12,193 --> 00:11:13,498
I love you.

117
00:11:13,542 --> 00:11:14,674
I love you too.

118
00:11:33,301 --> 00:11:34,955
-Hi.
-Hi.

119
00:11:38,698 --> 00:11:39,873
What are you doing?

120
00:11:39,916 --> 00:11:42,136
Oh, just cleaning up.

121
00:11:42,179 --> 00:11:44,704
Getting organized
for my big splash
in show business.

122
00:11:46,793 --> 00:11:48,359
You know, I wanted to thank you.

123
00:11:49,534 --> 00:11:52,015
Oh, yeah? For what?

124
00:11:52,059 --> 00:11:57,151
For moving 3,000 miles away
from home
so I could get a better job.

125
00:11:57,194 --> 00:12:00,371
For taking care of Chrissy
all the time
for the past few weeks.

126
00:12:01,895 --> 00:12:03,635
For being very flexible.

127
00:12:06,029 --> 00:12:07,030
Well,

128
00:12:08,031 --> 00:12:10,164
my career wasn't exactly...

129
00:12:11,034 --> 00:12:13,254
burning up the road in New York.

130
00:12:13,820 --> 00:12:15,430
So I didn't

131
00:12:15,473 --> 00:12:19,129
really have
all that much to lose.

132
00:12:19,173 --> 00:12:22,393
Well, things are gonna start
coming around for you,
I know it.

133
00:12:22,437 --> 00:12:24,526
-Yeah?
-Mm-hmm.

134
00:12:24,569 --> 00:12:27,311
-I mean, you have this whole
movie poster thing going.
-Mm-hmm.

135
00:12:28,356 --> 00:12:30,488
And a whole host
of fringe benefits.

136
00:12:31,881 --> 00:12:33,317
-Oh, yeah?
-Yeah.

137
00:12:37,321 --> 00:12:38,322
Like what?

138
00:12:41,151 --> 00:12:43,806
Like women are

139
00:12:43,850 --> 00:12:47,114
inexplicably attracted
to men who are in show business.

140
00:12:47,723 --> 00:12:48,724
Yeah?

141
00:13:18,232 --> 00:13:19,537
[KNOCKING AT DOOR]

142
00:13:19,581 --> 00:13:20,800
WOMAN: Hello?

143
00:13:20,843 --> 00:13:22,323
Ignore 'em. We're not home.

144
00:13:24,064 --> 00:13:25,282
[KNOCKING CONTINUES]

145
00:13:25,326 --> 00:13:26,675
-I really...
-WOMAN: Hello?

146
00:13:26,718 --> 00:13:28,851
We really should get it.
It's gonna wake Christina.

147
00:13:28,895 --> 00:13:30,505
[EXHALES]

148
00:13:30,548 --> 00:13:32,420
-[KNOCKING AT DOOR]
-Yeah.

149
00:13:45,825 --> 00:13:47,130
Mrs. Cowan?

150
00:13:47,478 --> 00:13:48,479
Yes.

151
00:13:50,046 --> 00:13:51,308
I'm Anna Bergman.

152
00:13:55,399 --> 00:13:56,574
The au pair.

153
00:13:57,924 --> 00:14:00,883
Oh. Anna, I'm sorry.
Please come in.

154
00:14:00,927 --> 00:14:02,232
NICK: Hey, no,
let me get those.

155
00:14:02,276 --> 00:14:03,451
ANNA: Oh, thank you.

156
00:14:03,494 --> 00:14:05,061
KATE: I'm Kate,
and this is Nick.

157
00:14:05,105 --> 00:14:06,802
-Hi.
-Hi.

158
00:14:06,846 --> 00:14:08,151
This is a surprise.

159
00:14:08,195 --> 00:14:09,892
Oh, well, yes.

160
00:14:09,936 --> 00:14:11,807
We weren't expecting you
for at least two days.

161
00:14:11,851 --> 00:14:15,158
I'm sorry. I hope I haven't
inconvenienced you.

162
00:14:15,202 --> 00:14:17,117
I called to confirm my flight,

163
00:14:17,160 --> 00:14:19,597
there was some kind of mix-up
with my reservations.

164
00:14:19,641 --> 00:14:21,686
Well, that's okay,
you're here now.

165
00:14:22,557 --> 00:14:23,558
Yes.

166
00:14:25,952 --> 00:14:27,779
-So...
-Please.

167
00:14:27,823 --> 00:14:29,869
Well, you have a beautiful home.

168
00:14:29,912 --> 00:14:31,958
Oh, thank you. You know,
you should have
called us from the airport.

169
00:14:32,001 --> 00:14:33,263
We would have picked you up.

170
00:14:33,307 --> 00:14:35,875
Please, there was no problem.
I took a taxi.

171
00:14:35,918 --> 00:14:37,746
It was a beautiful ride.

172
00:14:37,789 --> 00:14:42,664
Everything here is so rugged,
so wild-looking.

173
00:14:42,707 --> 00:14:44,927
Yeah, well, Nick's been
meaning to clean it up.

174
00:14:44,971 --> 00:14:47,277
Right. Yeah,
I got a lot of time for that.

175
00:14:48,409 --> 00:14:49,671
Excuse me.

176
00:14:54,328 --> 00:14:56,983
Well, you must be exhausted.
I'll show you your room.

177
00:15:02,684 --> 00:15:04,077
Here we are.

178
00:15:04,120 --> 00:15:06,079
Small, yet tiny.

179
00:15:11,606 --> 00:15:12,824
It's lovely.

180
00:15:14,087 --> 00:15:15,088
Really.

181
00:15:17,612 --> 00:15:20,049
Is Christina sleeping?

182
00:15:20,093 --> 00:15:23,444
Yes. She's gonna be
so disappointed
she missed your arrival.

183
00:15:23,487 --> 00:15:24,749
Oh.

184
00:15:24,793 --> 00:15:27,361
Well, I can't wait to meet her.

185
00:15:27,404 --> 00:15:29,754
Well, yes, in the morning.

186
00:15:29,798 --> 00:15:33,193
Listen, why don't you unpack,
and make yourself comfortable?

187
00:15:34,281 --> 00:15:35,282
Yeah.

188
00:15:39,721 --> 00:15:41,244
Is there anything wrong?

189
00:15:41,984 --> 00:15:43,638
No, I just...

190
00:15:43,681 --> 00:15:46,467
The keys for my suitcase,
I left them
in one of my pockets.

191
00:15:47,947 --> 00:15:49,252
Maybe it's in your purse.

192
00:15:52,473 --> 00:15:54,692
No, uh...

193
00:15:54,736 --> 00:15:57,957
I don't think so.
I put it in one of my pockets.

194
00:15:59,959 --> 00:16:01,743
Do you think you could
get these open for Anna?

195
00:16:02,787 --> 00:16:05,312
Sure. I'll just get my toolbox.

196
00:16:11,057 --> 00:16:13,711
I'm sorry, Mrs. Cowan.

197
00:16:13,755 --> 00:16:16,758
Kate. And, Anna, really,
it's no big deal.

198
00:16:18,281 --> 00:16:19,282
Yeah.

199
00:16:29,292 --> 00:16:30,685
Aren't you getting your tools?

200
00:16:32,643 --> 00:16:33,644
What?

201
00:16:34,645 --> 00:16:35,820
What do you mean, "What"?

202
00:16:37,083 --> 00:16:39,389
So, what do you think?

203
00:16:39,433 --> 00:16:43,480
-I think she seems sweet.
-Hmm, yeah.

204
00:16:43,524 --> 00:16:45,743
And not a heck of a lot going
on upstairs.

205
00:16:55,536 --> 00:16:56,798
[KNOCKING AT DOOR]

206
00:16:58,060 --> 00:16:59,061
Come in.

207
00:17:01,585 --> 00:17:03,196
Anna, this is Christina.

208
00:17:04,066 --> 00:17:05,546
Christina, this is Anna.

209
00:17:07,113 --> 00:17:08,505
ANNA: Well, hello there.

210
00:17:11,117 --> 00:17:12,683
KATE: Aren't you
gonna say hello?

211
00:17:13,467 --> 00:17:14,642
Hi.

212
00:17:14,685 --> 00:17:16,252
I'm very happy to meet you.

213
00:17:18,994 --> 00:17:20,909
Would you like to come in
and talk to me?

214
00:17:21,736 --> 00:17:22,737
Well, go ahead.

215
00:17:29,309 --> 00:17:33,182
You're awfully big.
How old are you?

216
00:17:33,226 --> 00:17:35,619
Twenty? Twenty-five?

217
00:17:35,663 --> 00:17:38,796
No, seven. Almost eight.
It's going to be
my birthday soon.

218
00:17:38,840 --> 00:17:40,015
Yeah, I know.

219
00:17:40,624 --> 00:17:42,409
July 24th.

220
00:17:42,452 --> 00:17:44,150
How did you know that?

221
00:17:44,193 --> 00:17:46,152
Well, your mother wrote
and told me.

222
00:17:49,068 --> 00:17:51,374
I wrote it in my diary,
so I wouldn't forget.

223
00:17:54,421 --> 00:17:55,465
See?

224
00:17:56,162 --> 00:17:57,902
Here we are.

225
00:17:57,946 --> 00:17:59,339
Christina's birthday.

226
00:18:00,992 --> 00:18:02,559
Well, I've got to get to work.

227
00:18:02,603 --> 00:18:04,692
But I can see the two of you
are gonna get along just fine.

228
00:18:04,735 --> 00:18:06,868
Yeah, I'm sure that we will.

229
00:18:07,738 --> 00:18:09,436
Okay, just a few things.

230
00:18:09,479 --> 00:18:11,264
The laundry's really piling up,

231
00:18:11,307 --> 00:18:12,961
so if you wouldn't mind
right after breakfast...

232
00:18:13,004 --> 00:18:15,137
-I'll take care of it.
-There's a lasagna
in the freezer.

233
00:18:15,181 --> 00:18:17,052
We'll have that
for dinner tonight.
I should be home about 6:30.

234
00:18:17,096 --> 00:18:18,662
I'll try not to be late,
'cause we like to eat at 7:00.

235
00:18:18,706 --> 00:18:21,012
-Okay, okay.
-My office number
is on the fridge.

236
00:18:21,056 --> 00:18:23,363
You can call me any time
and Nick will be working here
all day.

237
00:18:23,406 --> 00:18:25,321
I will be fine, Mrs. Cowan.

238
00:18:26,409 --> 00:18:28,498
KATE: Oh. The emergency numbers.

239
00:18:28,542 --> 00:18:31,327
Fire, police, ambulance,
you just dial 911.

240
00:18:31,371 --> 00:18:33,503
Thank you. I'm sure that
we won't need them.

241
00:18:36,245 --> 00:18:38,726
You be a good girl.
You listen to Anna.

242
00:18:38,769 --> 00:18:39,770
Okay.

243
00:18:46,473 --> 00:18:47,909
"Dear Mr. Monteiro,

244
00:18:47,952 --> 00:18:49,737
I am pleased to enclose a copy
of our draft contract

245
00:18:49,780 --> 00:18:51,913
for you to review
and comment upon."

246
00:18:51,956 --> 00:18:53,393
Hey, come on.
We've got to get going.

247
00:18:53,436 --> 00:18:55,090
Yeah, all right, just a sec.

248
00:18:55,134 --> 00:18:56,439
Where was I?

249
00:18:56,483 --> 00:18:59,486
"Contract for you to review
and comment upon."

250
00:18:59,529 --> 00:19:01,966
"Please call us
with your comments
at your earliest convenience.

251
00:19:02,010 --> 00:19:04,230
Sincerely, blah blah blah."
Thanks.

252
00:19:04,273 --> 00:19:06,014
I don't think I'm gonna
make it through this.

253
00:19:06,057 --> 00:19:07,929
When we get there,
they'll probably
keep us waiting half an hour,

254
00:19:07,972 --> 00:19:09,452
and then if we're five minutes
late, they'll throw a fit.

255
00:19:09,496 --> 00:19:10,758
-Oh, God.
-What?

256
00:19:10,801 --> 00:19:12,542
-I forgot to call Nick.
-Why?

257
00:19:12,586 --> 00:19:14,849
Anna, the au pair,
she started today.
I wanted to check in.

258
00:19:14,892 --> 00:19:16,981
Oh, come on.
No, we don't have time.
Let's go.

259
00:19:30,212 --> 00:19:32,475
[TELEPHONE RINGING]

260
00:19:35,217 --> 00:19:36,958
Hello.

261
00:19:37,001 --> 00:19:38,829
KATE: Hi, baby. 
I only have a minute. 
How's it going?

262
00:19:39,656 --> 00:19:41,528
You got to be kidding.

263
00:19:41,571 --> 00:19:43,530
What's the matter?

264
00:19:43,573 --> 00:19:46,489
NICK: The girl is a walking 
disaster area. 
That's what's the matter.

265
00:19:46,533 --> 00:19:48,578
-Anna?
-Yes, Anna.

266
00:19:48,622 --> 00:19:50,232
I spent more time
running around today

267
00:19:50,276 --> 00:19:51,712
than the last
three weeks combined.

268
00:19:51,755 --> 00:19:54,323
First we had a spoon 
jam up the garbage disposal,

269
00:19:54,367 --> 00:19:57,065
then she tried to heat up
a pot of soup in the microwave.

270
00:19:57,108 --> 00:19:59,459
Sparks flying everywhere.
It was like the Fourth of July.

271
00:19:59,502 --> 00:20:02,810
And to top it off, 
I spent the last hour knee-deep 
in suds,

272
00:20:02,853 --> 00:20:05,029
mopping up the flood 
from our washing machine.

273
00:20:05,073 --> 00:20:06,814
Oh, I'm sorry, honey.

274
00:20:06,857 --> 00:20:08,990
Do you want me to talk to her?
Put her on the phone.

275
00:20:09,033 --> 00:20:11,210
No, I can't. 
She's in her room, crying.

276
00:20:11,253 --> 00:20:13,473
Honey, I gotta go.
I'm gonna be late for a meeting.

277
00:20:13,516 --> 00:20:15,779
Can you just deal with this
until I get home, okay?

278
00:20:15,823 --> 00:20:17,477
Just until then, all right?

279
00:20:17,520 --> 00:20:19,043
Very easy for you to say.

280
00:20:20,001 --> 00:20:21,481
KATE: I love you.

281
00:20:21,524 --> 00:20:23,004
I love you, too.

282
00:21:03,087 --> 00:21:04,219
Hi, pumpkin.

283
00:21:04,263 --> 00:21:05,264
Hi, Mom.

284
00:21:06,656 --> 00:21:09,224
Guess what.
Anna broke the washing machine.

285
00:21:09,268 --> 00:21:10,878
It was a huge flood.

286
00:21:10,921 --> 00:21:12,488
Boy, was Daddy mad.

287
00:21:12,532 --> 00:21:14,360
Yeah, I heard. Where is Daddy?

288
00:21:14,403 --> 00:21:16,623
I don't know.
I think he's painting.

289
00:21:16,666 --> 00:21:18,364
Well, I have to go
take care of something.

290
00:21:18,407 --> 00:21:20,801
Could you please
put these cookies away
and clean up?

291
00:21:29,897 --> 00:21:30,941
Anna?

292
00:21:33,030 --> 00:21:34,771
What are you doing?

293
00:21:34,815 --> 00:21:38,819
I think it's best this way
that I go.

294
00:21:41,082 --> 00:21:43,563
Mr. Cowan is right to be angry.

295
00:21:44,955 --> 00:21:49,220
I just never had
such a big house
to take care of.

296
00:21:49,264 --> 00:21:52,789
Everything here
is so much more different
than it is at home.

297
00:21:56,967 --> 00:21:58,665
I'm sorry, Mrs. Cowan.

298
00:22:00,884 --> 00:22:02,190
I...

299
00:22:02,233 --> 00:22:04,366
I just wanted this job so much.

300
00:22:05,019 --> 00:22:06,977
I know.

301
00:22:07,021 --> 00:22:09,937
Anna, look. I understand
and Nick understands

302
00:22:09,980 --> 00:22:12,069
that this is a new experience
for you.

303
00:22:12,113 --> 00:22:13,984
You move to a new country,

304
00:22:14,028 --> 00:22:16,509
a family full of strangers,
an unfamiliar house.

305
00:22:16,552 --> 00:22:18,946
I mean, it's a big adjustment.

306
00:22:18,989 --> 00:22:20,948
We want this to work
as much as you do.

307
00:22:22,863 --> 00:22:25,779
I'm willing to give it
another shot if you are.

308
00:22:25,822 --> 00:22:28,347
What do you say?
Do we have a deal?

309
00:22:30,740 --> 00:22:31,741
Thank you.

310
00:22:36,311 --> 00:22:38,226
Well, I'll help you unpack.

311
00:22:38,269 --> 00:22:39,662
That's all right, Mrs. Cowan.

312
00:22:41,316 --> 00:22:43,231
I can do it. Thank you.

313
00:22:43,274 --> 00:22:46,365
Okay. Well, I'll go see about
getting some dinner
on the table.

314
00:23:04,295 --> 00:23:07,429
Yes, indeed, Mrs. Cowan.
We have a deal.

315
00:23:30,670 --> 00:23:32,846
DR. GROSBARD: Why did you take
so long to contact me?

316
00:23:32,889 --> 00:23:35,805
We thought
all of our girls were
accounted for, Dr. Grosbard.

317
00:23:35,849 --> 00:23:38,721
It wasn't until workmen
were clearing debris
from the fire

318
00:23:38,765 --> 00:23:40,375
that they found the body.

319
00:23:40,419 --> 00:23:43,509
Some of the girls had
already left
for the summer break.

320
00:23:43,552 --> 00:23:46,163
It was difficult to determine
who was missing.

321
00:23:46,207 --> 00:23:47,730
How did it start?

322
00:23:47,774 --> 00:23:51,081
There appears to have been
a gas leak in the science lab.

323
00:23:51,125 --> 00:23:53,432
-There was a terrible explosion.
-Oh.

324
00:23:53,475 --> 00:23:56,739
I know how difficult
this must be for you, Doctor.

325
00:23:56,783 --> 00:24:00,526
But you must believe and accept
that Kirsten is in God's grace.

326
00:24:00,569 --> 00:24:02,005
And where's her room?

327
00:24:03,180 --> 00:24:04,181
Mm-hmm.

328
00:24:09,752 --> 00:24:12,059
That was her desk.

329
00:24:12,102 --> 00:24:13,930
And this is where she slept.

330
00:24:23,026 --> 00:24:24,941
Were there any personal effects?

331
00:24:26,029 --> 00:24:29,250
Jewelry or a wristwatch?

332
00:24:29,293 --> 00:24:31,774
She wore a pendant
around her neck, always.

333
00:24:31,818 --> 00:24:33,472
Now it's not here.

334
00:24:34,255 --> 00:24:36,518
Perhaps she lost it.

335
00:24:36,562 --> 00:24:39,521
-Perhaps it was destroyed.
-Mm-hmm.

336
00:24:48,269 --> 00:24:49,879
Where is her passport?

337
00:24:49,923 --> 00:24:51,838
It must be here.

338
00:24:51,881 --> 00:24:53,535
Damn you! Damn you!

339
00:24:53,579 --> 00:24:55,319
You were supposed to watch her.

340
00:24:56,756 --> 00:24:59,454
Her roommate. Now, where is she?

341
00:24:59,498 --> 00:25:02,588
She's not here.
She left the night
of the accident.

342
00:25:02,631 --> 00:25:05,025
She left? Where?
Where? What is her name?

343
00:25:05,068 --> 00:25:06,417
Anna Bergman.

344
00:25:06,461 --> 00:25:10,465
She went to America
to work for a family there.

345
00:25:10,509 --> 00:25:12,598
Now, she and Kirsten.
Were they close?

346
00:25:13,163 --> 00:25:14,774
I suppose so.

347
00:25:14,817 --> 00:25:18,125
Kirsten asked to be switched
to her room several months ago.

348
00:25:18,995 --> 00:25:20,780
I want to see Kirsten.

349
00:25:20,823 --> 00:25:23,130
I would advise against it, 
HerrDoctor.

350
00:25:23,173 --> 00:25:26,742
She has been badly burned,
almost beyond recognition.

351
00:25:26,786 --> 00:25:29,005
The police report
is very thorough.

352
00:25:29,049 --> 00:25:30,485
If you would care
to look at it...

353
00:25:30,529 --> 00:25:32,226
I'm not interested
in the police report,

354
00:25:32,269 --> 00:25:34,924
and I am not interested
in your well-intentioned
recommendations.

355
00:25:34,968 --> 00:25:36,317
I want to see my daughter!

356
00:25:36,360 --> 00:25:38,362
Now, is that possible,
Reverend Mother?

357
00:25:40,408 --> 00:25:41,844
I'll make the arrangements.

358
00:25:59,383 --> 00:26:01,298
Her face has been
badly disfigured.

359
00:26:08,697 --> 00:26:09,916
That is not Kirsten.

360
00:26:11,700 --> 00:26:13,049
That is not my daughter.

361
00:26:41,687 --> 00:26:43,297
Paragraph six.

362
00:26:43,340 --> 00:26:45,865
"The rights granted
to you hereunder
are personal

363
00:26:45,908 --> 00:26:47,693
and shall not be assigned
by you

364
00:26:47,736 --> 00:26:50,696
in any part
to any third party."

365
00:26:50,739 --> 00:26:54,134
You know, I think I'm actually
learning to like the taste
of Styrofoam.

366
00:26:55,396 --> 00:26:57,267
Excuse me.
It's Nick on line one.

367
00:27:00,096 --> 00:27:01,358
Stay calm, baby.

368
00:27:02,185 --> 00:27:03,186
No.

369
00:27:09,018 --> 00:27:10,541
Hi, baby. What's up?

370
00:27:10,585 --> 00:27:12,065
Well, I got some good news
and some bad news.

371
00:27:12,108 --> 00:27:13,196
Which you want first?

372
00:27:13,240 --> 00:27:15,329
-Give me the good. 
-Okay.

373
00:27:15,372 --> 00:27:18,027
Sid called.
The last guy signed off.

374
00:27:18,071 --> 00:27:19,638
They approved my sketches.

375
00:27:19,681 --> 00:27:21,944
Well, Nick, that's wonderful.

376
00:27:21,988 --> 00:27:23,598
So what about the bad news?

377
00:27:23,642 --> 00:27:25,687
The bad news is
they approved my sketches.

378
00:27:25,731 --> 00:27:29,082
So, now I've got to do
the damn thing,
and I'm stuck.

379
00:27:29,125 --> 00:27:31,998
KATE: You'll be okay. 
You know you always start off 
like this.

380
00:27:32,041 --> 00:27:34,435
I thought you were calling
with some horror story
about Anna.

381
00:27:34,478 --> 00:27:36,045
No, actually, she's okay.

382
00:27:36,089 --> 00:27:37,699
I don't know what you said
to her the other day,

383
00:27:37,743 --> 00:27:39,614
but so far, no major screw-ups.

384
00:27:39,658 --> 00:27:42,965
Well, do you think you trust her
enough to make Chrissy
and you dinner?

385
00:27:44,619 --> 00:27:47,013
Why? You working late again?

386
00:27:47,056 --> 00:27:49,493
You know I don't like it
any more than you do,

387
00:27:49,537 --> 00:27:51,234
but I'll be home 
as soon as I can.

388
00:27:51,887 --> 00:27:52,888
Mm-hmm.

389
00:27:53,541 --> 00:27:54,542
Nick,

390
00:27:56,152 --> 00:27:57,197
I adore you.

391
00:27:58,633 --> 00:28:00,766
Yeah. Talk to you later.

392
00:28:06,032 --> 00:28:08,208
What, another flood? Your family
floating around the living room?

393
00:28:09,731 --> 00:28:13,430
No. I think our little Anna's
gonna work out just fine.

394
00:28:13,474 --> 00:28:14,475
Yeah?

395
00:28:14,910 --> 00:28:15,955
Yeah.

396
00:28:16,651 --> 00:28:17,913
[GROWLS]

397
00:28:17,957 --> 00:28:19,698
[LAUGHS]

398
00:28:19,741 --> 00:28:22,788
Excuse me.
Do you have an aspirin?
I have a splitting headache.

399
00:28:22,831 --> 00:28:24,050
[BOTH LAUGH]

400
00:28:24,093 --> 00:28:27,053
Pardon me. Would you
pass the cheese, please?

401
00:28:28,968 --> 00:28:30,447
Oh!

402
00:28:30,491 --> 00:28:33,537
Christina, you have some
wonderful costumes here.

403
00:28:36,540 --> 00:28:37,890
You know what?

404
00:28:37,933 --> 00:28:40,544
I have just the perfect thing
to add to it.

405
00:28:42,111 --> 00:28:43,112
Come on.

406
00:28:46,725 --> 00:28:47,856
What do you think?

407
00:28:48,988 --> 00:28:51,207
You look very sophisticated.

408
00:28:51,251 --> 00:28:52,992
I think I need some lipstick.

409
00:28:53,035 --> 00:28:54,428
It's on the dresser.

410
00:28:59,999 --> 00:29:01,261
[GRUNTS]

411
00:29:06,396 --> 00:29:08,747
Chrissy, look at this.

412
00:29:10,661 --> 00:29:13,403
-Oh, it's pretty.
-Do you like it?

413
00:29:17,407 --> 00:29:19,235
This was my dress at your age.

414
00:29:21,716 --> 00:29:23,936
Look at that.
It almost fits.

415
00:29:25,067 --> 00:29:26,547
Here, come see in the mirror.

416
00:29:33,641 --> 00:29:37,688
Oh, it's beautiful.
You look just like a bride.

417
00:29:37,732 --> 00:29:39,255
-Do I really?
-Yeah.

418
00:29:40,343 --> 00:29:42,084
I'm going
to get married someday.

419
00:29:42,128 --> 00:29:44,434
Well, I know you are.

420
00:29:44,478 --> 00:29:48,003
You know, Chrissy,
when you get married,
it's a big responsibility.

421
00:29:48,047 --> 00:29:50,397
You have to devote your life
to your husband,

422
00:29:50,440 --> 00:29:51,964
become his soul mate,

423
00:29:53,356 --> 00:29:55,794
and do everything in your power
to make him happy.

424
00:29:56,795 --> 00:29:58,144
How will I know what to do?

425
00:30:00,886 --> 00:30:02,104
You'll find out.

426
00:30:11,635 --> 00:30:13,333
Excuse me.

427
00:30:13,376 --> 00:30:15,378
Do you work in this office?

428
00:30:15,422 --> 00:30:17,163
Yes, but I'm sorry.
We're closed.

429
00:30:17,206 --> 00:30:19,078
No, I understand,
but perhaps you can
help me anyway.

430
00:30:19,121 --> 00:30:21,471
I'm trying to find a girl.

431
00:30:21,515 --> 00:30:23,125
Well, if you come in tomorrow,
Dr. Grosbard,

432
00:30:23,169 --> 00:30:24,344
you can fill in an application.

433
00:30:24,387 --> 00:30:26,172
No, you see, she works for you.

434
00:30:26,215 --> 00:30:28,783
You've placed her
with an American family.
Her name is Anna Bergman.

435
00:30:28,827 --> 00:30:31,873
We place many girls here,
but I'm sure you understand,

436
00:30:31,917 --> 00:30:34,615
details of the transactions
must remain
strictly confidential.

437
00:30:34,658 --> 00:30:36,922
Listen, I understand,
but this is an entirely
different situation.

438
00:30:36,965 --> 00:30:38,880
My daughter has run away,

439
00:30:38,924 --> 00:30:40,708
and she and Anna Bergman
were close friends.

440
00:30:40,751 --> 00:30:42,362
In fact, they were best friends.

441
00:30:42,405 --> 00:30:44,364
So I was hoping
that Anna would know
where she has gone.

442
00:30:44,407 --> 00:30:46,932
I'm sorry, Dr. Grosbard.
Truly, I am.

443
00:30:46,975 --> 00:30:48,803
You don't understand.
There is not much time.

444
00:30:48,847 --> 00:30:50,283
You must tell me where she is.

445
00:30:50,326 --> 00:30:52,894
I'm sorry. I cannot help you.
Please let me go.

446
00:30:52,938 --> 00:30:55,375
But you can call her, can't you?

447
00:30:55,418 --> 00:30:58,987
I can call a policeman
if you don't let me go.

448
00:30:59,031 --> 00:31:02,382
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.
Please, will you help me?
Please?

449
00:31:03,992 --> 00:31:07,039
Fine. I'll call her.
Check with me tomorrow.

450
00:31:07,082 --> 00:31:08,475
Yes, but tomorrow could be...

451
00:31:08,518 --> 00:31:10,738
I'll call tomorrow
and let you know
what I find out.

452
00:31:10,781 --> 00:31:11,870
Thank you.

453
00:31:33,239 --> 00:31:34,240
Nick?

454
00:31:35,458 --> 00:31:36,503
In here.

455
00:31:41,464 --> 00:31:43,162
-What is this?
-Entrer, madame.

456
00:31:43,727 --> 00:31:45,251
What's going on?

457
00:31:45,294 --> 00:31:48,167
Well, it seems that Mary Poppins

458
00:31:48,210 --> 00:31:51,126
finally waved
her magic umbrella.

459
00:31:51,170 --> 00:31:53,781
Swedish fruit soup,
with a dollop of sour cream.

460
00:31:53,824 --> 00:31:55,870
Poached salmon
with a little fresh dill.

461
00:31:55,914 --> 00:32:00,048
And we even have a very special
home-made plum pudding
with brandy sauce.

462
00:32:01,745 --> 00:32:03,269
Anna did all this?

463
00:32:03,312 --> 00:32:05,401
Cooked it, baked it,
spent half the day
shopping for it,

464
00:32:05,445 --> 00:32:07,882
and you should see
the dinner she made
for Christina.

465
00:32:07,926 --> 00:32:09,971
Well, I'm impressed.
What can I say?

466
00:32:10,015 --> 00:32:11,581
You can say you're relieved.

467
00:32:11,625 --> 00:32:13,409
At least the girl knows
how to do something right.

468
00:32:13,453 --> 00:32:14,976
Well, there was never a doubt
in my mind.

469
00:32:15,020 --> 00:32:17,979
No? Never?
Not even just a little?

470
00:32:18,023 --> 00:32:19,633
[CHUCKLES]

471
00:32:19,676 --> 00:32:20,982
I'm gonna go say good night
to Chrissy.

472
00:32:22,114 --> 00:32:23,115
Okay.

473
00:32:25,247 --> 00:32:27,162
KATE: And don't touch
any of that food
until I get back.

474
00:32:35,518 --> 00:32:37,390
-Hi, Mom.
-Hi, pumpkin.

475
00:32:37,433 --> 00:32:39,044
Anna.

476
00:32:39,087 --> 00:32:41,872
Anna's been showing me
all these neat pictures
of Sweden.

477
00:32:41,916 --> 00:32:44,223
The snow and mountains,

478
00:32:44,266 --> 00:32:46,486
and sleds and horses.

479
00:32:48,314 --> 00:32:50,403
Well, Anna's been doing
all kinds of neat things today.

480
00:32:50,446 --> 00:32:52,274
It was a beautiful dinner
you prepared. Thank you.

481
00:32:52,318 --> 00:32:54,450
It's my pleasure, Mrs. Cowan.

482
00:32:54,494 --> 00:32:56,322
Will you read me
a bedtime story tonight?

483
00:32:56,365 --> 00:32:57,540
Well, sure, I'd love to.

484
00:32:59,368 --> 00:33:02,110
Well, in that case,
I'll say good night.

485
00:33:02,154 --> 00:33:05,548
And will save my story
for some other time.

486
00:33:05,592 --> 00:33:07,550
Oh, were you gonna
read to her, Anna?

487
00:33:07,594 --> 00:33:10,858
Oh, it's all right.
It's not important.

488
00:33:10,901 --> 00:33:13,252
Chrissy, why don't you let Anna
read to you tonight?

489
00:33:13,295 --> 00:33:15,254
Daddy and I
haven't had our dinner yet.

490
00:33:15,297 --> 00:33:17,169
I can read to you
tomorrow night, okay?

491
00:33:17,212 --> 00:33:18,213
I guess.

492
00:33:19,214 --> 00:33:20,433
-Good night.
-Good night.

493
00:33:20,476 --> 00:33:21,782
Good night, Anna.

494
00:33:21,825 --> 00:33:24,350
Good night, Mrs. Cowan,
and enjoy your dinner.

495
00:33:28,702 --> 00:33:30,051
What would you like to read?

496
00:33:30,095 --> 00:33:31,444
-This one.
-Okay.

497
00:33:36,318 --> 00:33:37,928
You look fantastic.

498
00:33:43,978 --> 00:33:47,329
May I suggest, madam,
before the soup,

499
00:33:47,373 --> 00:33:51,507
Miss Anna's home-brewed
lingonberry wine?

500
00:33:51,551 --> 00:33:53,596
It's a very amusing
vintage, actually.

501
00:33:53,640 --> 00:33:55,381
Hmm. What year?

502
00:33:55,424 --> 00:33:58,079
-Week ago Tuesday.
-[LAUGHS]

503
00:33:58,123 --> 00:33:59,863
It was a very good day
for lingonberries.

504
00:34:00,342 --> 00:34:01,343
Skol.

505
00:34:09,003 --> 00:34:11,179
Hmm, tad on the sweet side.

506
00:34:11,223 --> 00:34:13,094
Yeah, just a touch.

507
00:34:15,705 --> 00:34:16,750
But it's good.

508
00:34:17,881 --> 00:34:19,057
It grows on you.

509
00:34:21,363 --> 00:34:22,408
Yeah?

510
00:34:22,451 --> 00:34:23,974
[BOTH LAUGHING]

511
00:34:31,199 --> 00:34:33,027
What's this?

512
00:34:33,071 --> 00:34:34,898
That's just
some drawings of mine.

513
00:34:35,943 --> 00:34:37,684
What kind of drawings?

514
00:34:37,727 --> 00:34:39,729
Sort of like...

515
00:34:39,773 --> 00:34:42,297
a fairytale, about a princess.

516
00:34:43,603 --> 00:34:44,908
Can we read it?

517
00:34:44,952 --> 00:34:46,084
Sure, if you like.

518
00:35:00,185 --> 00:35:01,447
Oh, it's pretty.

519
00:35:03,231 --> 00:35:05,625
Where are the words?

520
00:35:05,668 --> 00:35:08,367
Well, we read the pictures
and they give us the words.

521
00:35:08,410 --> 00:35:10,108
Now,

522
00:35:10,151 --> 00:35:15,156
once upon a time,
there was a beautiful
young girl...

523
00:35:15,200 --> 00:35:17,027
With pretty hair.

524
00:35:17,071 --> 00:35:18,899
...who lived
in the forest with her...

525
00:35:19,813 --> 00:35:21,075
CHRISTINA: Mother and father.

526
00:35:26,733 --> 00:35:29,083
And as she was walking
through the woods,

527
00:35:29,127 --> 00:35:30,780
something caught her eye.

528
00:35:31,999 --> 00:35:33,131
What is it?

529
00:35:34,044 --> 00:35:36,351
ANNA: Hanging from a branch,

530
00:35:36,395 --> 00:35:38,397
at the end of a golden chain,

531
00:35:38,440 --> 00:35:39,746
there was a pendant.

532
00:35:40,442 --> 00:35:41,617
Pendant?

533
00:35:43,532 --> 00:35:44,533
Like this.

534
00:35:49,495 --> 00:35:53,455
Except, the one
on the branch bark was like
the colors of the rainbow.

535
00:35:54,500 --> 00:35:56,284
But who did it belong to?

536
00:36:00,375 --> 00:36:02,725
Oh, he's handsome.

537
00:36:02,769 --> 00:36:03,813
ANNA: Isn't he?

538
00:36:04,640 --> 00:36:06,164
He's a real prince.

539
00:36:07,208 --> 00:36:08,731
And this pendant is a gift

540
00:36:08,775 --> 00:36:12,039
that he gives to the girl
who would be his bride.

541
00:36:12,082 --> 00:36:13,649
But who gave you your pendant?

542
00:36:15,303 --> 00:36:17,479
Well, that's a secret.

543
00:36:17,523 --> 00:36:19,394
I won't tell.

544
00:36:19,438 --> 00:36:21,527
Well, if I tell you, Christina,

545
00:36:21,570 --> 00:36:23,224
you must promise
not to tell anyone.

546
00:36:23,268 --> 00:36:25,052
Not even
your mother or your father.

547
00:36:25,095 --> 00:36:26,575
I won't. I promise.

548
00:36:32,190 --> 00:36:33,669
I was married once.

549
00:36:35,367 --> 00:36:37,369
-You were?
-Yeah.

550
00:36:37,412 --> 00:36:39,066
You're awfully young.

551
00:36:39,109 --> 00:36:42,417
Well, maybe, but it was
the most important day
of my life.

552
00:36:43,026 --> 00:36:44,245
Who'd you marry?

553
00:36:44,289 --> 00:36:45,855
He was a prince.

554
00:36:45,899 --> 00:36:48,728
-Get out of here.
-No, I'm serious.

555
00:36:48,771 --> 00:36:52,340
A real prince,
and a very powerful man.

556
00:36:53,298 --> 00:36:54,734
And he chose me

557
00:36:54,777 --> 00:36:58,303
out of all the girls
in his kingdom to be his bride.

558
00:36:58,346 --> 00:37:00,653
What happened to him?
Where is he now?

559
00:37:01,567 --> 00:37:03,482
My father took me away from him.

560
00:37:04,091 --> 00:37:05,092
Why?

561
00:37:07,399 --> 00:37:08,574
I don't know.

562
00:37:11,707 --> 00:37:15,842
[SIGHS] But this pendant
is something we both share.

563
00:37:15,885 --> 00:37:17,322
It ties us together.

564
00:37:18,671 --> 00:37:21,674
And no matter how far away
my father takes me,

565
00:37:21,717 --> 00:37:24,067
my prince and I
will always be together.

566
00:37:24,111 --> 00:37:25,721
That's so romantic.

567
00:37:26,374 --> 00:37:28,463
Yeah.

568
00:37:28,507 --> 00:37:32,380
Maybe one day,
when you have your prince,

569
00:37:32,424 --> 00:37:33,947
you'll have one of these.

570
00:37:34,774 --> 00:37:37,080
Would you like that? Yeah?

571
00:37:37,820 --> 00:37:38,821
Okay.

572
00:37:41,259 --> 00:37:42,260
Some day.

573
00:38:02,845 --> 00:38:05,805
CHRISTINA: And she goes
to look for the prince,
but that mean spirit,

574
00:38:05,848 --> 00:38:09,504
the one who doesn't want her
to find him,
gets her lost in the woods.

575
00:38:09,548 --> 00:38:10,940
KATE: Hmm, sounds frightening.

576
00:38:11,854 --> 00:38:13,291
Thank you, Anna.

577
00:38:13,334 --> 00:38:15,075
ANNA: Would you like
some more pancakes, Mrs. Cowan?

578
00:38:15,118 --> 00:38:16,772
No. No, but they're wonderful.

579
00:38:16,816 --> 00:38:18,208
How about you, Chrissy?

580
00:38:18,252 --> 00:38:19,645
-I think Chrissy's had enough.
-Yes, please.

581
00:38:19,688 --> 00:38:21,908
Okay, coming right up, miss.

582
00:38:21,951 --> 00:38:22,952
Anna.

583
00:38:25,085 --> 00:38:26,652
Just one more for Chrissy.

584
00:38:27,479 --> 00:38:28,523
All right.

585
00:38:33,398 --> 00:38:34,442
So what happened next?

586
00:38:34,486 --> 00:38:36,096
So she gets lost in the woods,

587
00:38:36,139 --> 00:38:38,141
and her father goes
to look for her.

588
00:38:38,185 --> 00:38:39,882
But that mean spirit

589
00:38:39,926 --> 00:38:43,582
makes the forest all black.
Like it's night.

590
00:38:43,625 --> 00:38:48,195
And that's when the prince
comes along on his beautiful
horse and saves her.

591
00:38:48,238 --> 00:38:50,458
"Oh, the prince."
Did I hear someone
call my name?

592
00:38:50,502 --> 00:38:52,765
No, Daddy,
you're not the prince.

593
00:38:52,808 --> 00:38:53,940
The prince is handsome.

594
00:38:54,810 --> 00:38:57,160
Thank you, sweetheart.

595
00:38:57,204 --> 00:38:59,380
CHRISTINA: The prince
was in Anna's picture story.

596
00:38:59,424 --> 00:39:01,513
Anna's an excellent artist.

597
00:39:01,556 --> 00:39:02,731
I'm sure she is.

598
00:39:06,387 --> 00:39:08,563
Anna, you should
show your drawings to Daddy.

599
00:39:08,607 --> 00:39:09,825
He's an artist too.

600
00:39:12,524 --> 00:39:14,613
It's just a hobby, really.

601
00:39:14,656 --> 00:39:16,266
Something that I do for myself.

602
00:39:17,398 --> 00:39:19,357
Uh-huh. This looks great.

603
00:39:20,358 --> 00:39:21,533
What's today's date?

604
00:39:22,098 --> 00:39:23,361
The 20th. Why?

605
00:39:25,363 --> 00:39:28,366
Four more days
to Mystery Mountain.

606
00:39:28,409 --> 00:39:31,151
Well, I don't think
we're very anxious, are we?

607
00:39:31,194 --> 00:39:33,458
Listen, I've gotta go.
You have a good day.

608
00:39:33,501 --> 00:39:34,633
Bye.

609
00:39:34,676 --> 00:39:37,244
And you have a breakthrough.

610
00:39:50,649 --> 00:39:52,346
-[KNOCKING AT DOOR]
-It's open.

611
00:39:59,440 --> 00:40:00,398
Hi.

612
00:40:03,792 --> 00:40:05,881
Hope I'm not disturbing you.

613
00:40:05,925 --> 00:40:08,580
No. You can't disturb somebody
who isn't doing anything.

614
00:40:08,623 --> 00:40:09,624
What's up?

615
00:40:10,756 --> 00:40:12,497
I thought you might
like some coffee.

616
00:40:12,540 --> 00:40:14,455
Thanks. Coffee sounds great.

617
00:40:22,768 --> 00:40:25,205
-This is quite impressive.
-Mm.

618
00:40:26,119 --> 00:40:27,425
Yeah. Thanks.

619
00:40:30,079 --> 00:40:31,907
I like this one.
It's interesting.

620
00:40:32,473 --> 00:40:34,083
Key art.

621
00:40:34,127 --> 00:40:36,172
It's a one-sheet
for a movie poster.

622
00:40:37,217 --> 00:40:38,305
For the cinema?

623
00:40:38,348 --> 00:40:40,655
Yeah, it will be,
if I ever finish it.

624
00:40:40,699 --> 00:40:43,005
I just can't seem
to get a sense of...

625
00:40:44,267 --> 00:40:45,747
I can't get a handle on it.

626
00:40:47,270 --> 00:40:49,447
Wait. What is the film about?

627
00:40:49,490 --> 00:40:52,232
It's a thriller
about a family under siege.

628
00:40:52,275 --> 00:40:54,887
I've painted this damn thing
six times.

629
00:40:54,930 --> 00:40:58,064
This is the worst one, actually.
It look like they're

630
00:40:58,107 --> 00:41:00,240
posing for a Christmas card.

631
00:41:04,462 --> 00:41:05,767
Well, thanks for the coffee.

632
00:41:11,120 --> 00:41:13,079
I brought the drawings.

633
00:41:13,122 --> 00:41:15,081
The drawings. Oh, right.

634
00:41:16,212 --> 00:41:17,475
Your drawings.

635
00:41:17,518 --> 00:41:19,520
If this is a bad time,
I can come back, or...

636
00:41:19,564 --> 00:41:21,479
No, that's okay.

637
00:41:21,522 --> 00:41:22,784
Let's have a look.

638
00:41:22,828 --> 00:41:25,395
These are not
exactly professional.

639
00:41:30,488 --> 00:41:32,141
I'm sorry. It's the other way.

640
00:41:40,628 --> 00:41:41,803
Hmm.

641
00:41:44,153 --> 00:41:45,590
I like this.

642
00:41:45,633 --> 00:41:47,330
-Really?
-Really.

643
00:41:49,811 --> 00:41:51,421
Can you see what's happening?

644
00:41:54,686 --> 00:41:57,732
Well, it's a man in the dark.

645
00:41:58,777 --> 00:42:00,561
A forest. He's in the forest.

646
00:42:01,736 --> 00:42:03,346
And he's lost something.

647
00:42:04,652 --> 00:42:05,697
His daughter.

648
00:42:06,959 --> 00:42:08,569
He's searching for his daughter.

649
00:42:11,920 --> 00:42:15,228
I like the way you've
obscured the forest,
and hidden things in the trees.

650
00:42:15,271 --> 00:42:17,839
It's almost like you can see her
hiding in the shadows.

651
00:42:19,798 --> 00:42:22,148
It's as though he were
afraid of the darkness

652
00:42:22,191 --> 00:42:23,584
but drawn towards it.

653
00:42:25,978 --> 00:42:28,807
Well, sort of like the poster.

654
00:42:32,332 --> 00:42:35,030
Excuse me if I sound
so presumptuous.

655
00:42:35,074 --> 00:42:36,554
No, no, no, that's okay.

656
00:42:37,250 --> 00:42:38,599
Or perhaps if...

657
00:42:40,732 --> 00:42:43,648
...the background
was a little less defined

658
00:42:43,691 --> 00:42:47,042
so that the family is drawn
to the darkness.

659
00:42:48,261 --> 00:42:49,697
Even though it's frightening.

660
00:42:51,525 --> 00:42:53,396
Because there's safety
in the shadows.

661
00:43:02,318 --> 00:43:03,885
I must go back to work now.

662
00:43:25,864 --> 00:43:27,648
[TELEPHONE RINGING]

663
00:43:30,433 --> 00:43:32,000
Yeah. Hello?

664
00:43:32,044 --> 00:43:34,829
WOMAN: Oh, good morning. 
This is the Au pair exchange

665
00:43:34,873 --> 00:43:36,570
calling from Stockholm.

666
00:43:36,614 --> 00:43:38,180
Is Mrs. Cowan there, please?

667
00:43:39,747 --> 00:43:41,096
Speaking.

668
00:43:41,140 --> 00:43:43,142
I'm sorry to disturb you, 
Mrs. Cowan,

669
00:43:43,185 --> 00:43:44,970
but I have a gentleman here,

670
00:43:45,013 --> 00:43:47,146
-a Dr. Grosbard.
-DR. GROSBARD: Grosbard.

671
00:43:47,189 --> 00:43:49,539
He's trying
to contact Anna Bergman.

672
00:43:49,583 --> 00:43:51,193
Is she available?

673
00:43:51,237 --> 00:43:52,891
I'm afraid she's gone out.

674
00:43:53,718 --> 00:43:55,937
Perhaps I can help you.

675
00:43:55,981 --> 00:44:00,246
Well, it seems that Anna
is a friend of his daughter.

676
00:44:00,289 --> 00:44:02,640
-Kirsten.
-Kirsten Grosbard.

677
00:44:02,683 --> 00:44:05,468
-She has disappeared.
-Oh, how awful!

678
00:44:05,512 --> 00:44:08,558
And he thought that Anna 
might have some idea 
where she was.

679
00:44:09,821 --> 00:44:12,214
Look, why don't you give me
the information,

680
00:44:12,258 --> 00:44:15,261
and when Anna returns,
I'll have her

681
00:44:15,304 --> 00:44:17,089
call him, okay?

682
00:44:17,132 --> 00:44:18,699
WOMAN: Do you have a pencil?

683
00:44:18,743 --> 00:44:19,918
Right here.

684
00:44:19,961 --> 00:44:23,443
-It's Dr. Stefan Grosbard. 
-Grosbard.

685
00:44:23,486 --> 00:44:25,750
-Telephone... 
-I'll give you the number.

686
00:44:25,793 --> 00:44:27,360
011

687
00:44:27,403 --> 00:44:28,491
-4...
-Excuse me.

688
00:44:28,535 --> 00:44:30,232
Hello. This is
Dr. Grosbard speaking.

689
00:44:30,276 --> 00:44:32,670
This is Kirsten's father,
and I must speak
with Anna immediately.

690
00:44:32,713 --> 00:44:35,585
It's a matter
of great emergency.

691
00:44:35,629 --> 00:44:38,588
It is absolutely imperative 
that I speak to her 
without delay.

692
00:44:41,722 --> 00:44:42,680
Damn it.

693
00:44:43,506 --> 00:44:44,682
Damn them!

694
00:44:58,521 --> 00:45:00,001
-Hi.
-Hi.

695
00:45:00,045 --> 00:45:01,089
I'm home.

696
00:45:03,396 --> 00:45:04,876
Oh, strong. I like it.

697
00:45:04,919 --> 00:45:06,834
Yeah.

698
00:45:06,878 --> 00:45:08,706
It's the craziest thing.
Anna came in here
to show me one of her drawings,

699
00:45:08,749 --> 00:45:10,751
which are very good.
She's got talent.

700
00:45:10,795 --> 00:45:13,362
And one of them
just set me off.

701
00:45:13,406 --> 00:45:15,974
-Really?
-It's very interesting.

702
00:45:16,017 --> 00:45:18,367
You change the light,
you change the whole thing.

703
00:45:20,456 --> 00:45:23,155
You want to take a break?
Want to get something
to eat with me?

704
00:45:23,198 --> 00:45:24,286
No.

705
00:45:24,330 --> 00:45:27,246
Actually, honey,
I ate already. Thanks.

706
00:45:27,289 --> 00:45:30,205
You did? Well, you wanna
keep me company while I eat?

707
00:45:30,249 --> 00:45:32,555
No, I really want to
nail this before I lose it.

708
00:45:32,599 --> 00:45:33,731
You don't mind, do you?

709
00:45:34,862 --> 00:45:36,951
No, of course not.

710
00:45:36,995 --> 00:45:39,040
-I'll see you inside.
-Uh-huh.

711
00:45:50,530 --> 00:45:53,141
-Hi.
-Hi.

712
00:45:53,185 --> 00:45:56,057
All washed up?
Let me look
at those pearly whites.

713
00:45:57,276 --> 00:45:59,321
Oh. Can I see
the back ones?

714
00:46:00,148 --> 00:46:01,671
Dazzling.

715
00:46:01,715 --> 00:46:03,238
How about I read you
a special story tonight?

716
00:46:03,282 --> 00:46:04,674
A couple of chapters
of Charlotte's Web.

717
00:46:05,414 --> 00:46:07,460
Well, maybe tomorrow.

718
00:46:07,503 --> 00:46:09,636
Anna's waiting for me.
She's going to tell me
some more of her picture story.

719
00:46:11,159 --> 00:46:13,901
Oh, all right. Well, then,
let's brush that hair then.

720
00:46:13,945 --> 00:46:16,774
Mom, Anna did it already.
Can't you tell?

721
00:46:17,862 --> 00:46:18,906
Oh.

722
00:46:20,081 --> 00:46:22,040
Well, how about
a good night hug then?

723
00:46:22,083 --> 00:46:23,432
Good night, Mom.

724
00:46:31,701 --> 00:46:32,833
[SIGHS]

725
00:48:04,446 --> 00:48:05,491
You're still up.

726
00:48:06,405 --> 00:48:07,841
I wanted to wait for you.

727
00:48:17,938 --> 00:48:19,374
Did you finish up?

728
00:48:19,418 --> 00:48:20,636
For today, yeah.

729
00:48:26,468 --> 00:48:27,469
[GROANS]

730
00:48:30,211 --> 00:48:31,909
Would you rub my neck, honey?

731
00:48:33,388 --> 00:48:35,260
I'm feeling a little tense.

732
00:48:39,307 --> 00:48:40,439
Tough day?

733
00:48:41,353 --> 00:48:42,441
Brutal.

734
00:48:45,226 --> 00:48:46,793
That feels good.

735
00:48:53,104 --> 00:48:54,409
Too many hours.

736
00:49:01,416 --> 00:49:02,896
I've been missing you.

737
00:49:06,247 --> 00:49:08,249
Yeah, I've been missing you too.

738
00:50:54,921 --> 00:50:56,444
[ALARM RINGING]

739
00:51:01,014 --> 00:51:02,059
What time is it?

740
00:51:03,669 --> 00:51:05,540
It's quarter to 8:00.

741
00:51:05,584 --> 00:51:08,543
I can't believe you have to
go to work today.

742
00:51:08,587 --> 00:51:10,589
Even God took a day off,
you know?

743
00:51:22,905 --> 00:51:24,472
It's 8:00, Christina.

744
00:51:24,516 --> 00:51:26,257
If you want breakfast,
you're gonna
have to come in now.

745
00:51:31,088 --> 00:51:32,480
Hi, Mom. Good morning.

746
00:51:32,524 --> 00:51:34,178
Good morning, honey.

747
00:51:34,221 --> 00:51:36,615
Oh, good morning, Mrs. Cowan.

748
00:51:36,658 --> 00:51:38,356
Would you care
for some breakfast?

749
00:51:39,270 --> 00:51:40,401
No, thank you, Anna.

750
00:51:41,272 --> 00:51:43,012
Isn't today your day off?

751
00:51:43,056 --> 00:51:46,712
Well, I was up
and Christina was hungry.

752
00:51:46,755 --> 00:51:50,063
Maybe let me get you at least
some coffee or some toast.

753
00:51:50,107 --> 00:51:52,413
No, thank you.
I'll get something
at the office.

754
00:51:52,457 --> 00:51:54,111
-Have a good day, pumpkin.
-Bye.

755
00:51:58,202 --> 00:51:59,681
Have a nice day, Mrs. Cowan.

756
00:52:03,294 --> 00:52:04,773
[INAUDIBLE CONVERSATION]

757
00:52:06,427 --> 00:52:07,776
[BOTH LAUGHING]

758
00:52:18,744 --> 00:52:20,920
ANNA: But it's nice if you
have a bit of contrast.

759
00:52:20,963 --> 00:52:22,791
If the prince
is with the dark hair,

760
00:52:22,835 --> 00:52:24,793
-then the princess
has more light.
-CHRISTINA: Okay.

